What is Spring Batch?
Spring Batch is a lightweight, comprehensive batch processing framework built on top of Spring.
It handles large-volume data operations — reading from a source, transforming it, and writing to a destination — in a reliable, restartable, and monitorable way.

Why Spring Batch over the Old Way?
Before Spring Batch, teams wrote batch jobs as plain Java main() methods with manual loops, hand-coded JDBC, and DIY retry logic. 
Here's the honest comparison:
OLD WAY                          SPRING BATCH
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
No structure                  → Job → Step → Reader/Processor/Writer
Manual restart from scratch   → Resumes from last failed step (JobRepository)
Hand-coded chunking loops     → Built-in chunk-oriented processing
DIY retry/skip logic          → Declarative skip policies and retry policies
No monitoring                 → Full JobExecution / StepExecution metadata
Thread-safety DIY             → Partitioning, parallel steps, TaskExecutor
Reinvented every project      → Pre-built readers/writers for JDBC, JPA, CSV, XML

Scheduling a Job in Spring Boot (With Examples)
1. Enable Scheduling
  We enable scheduling using @EnableScheduling in the main class.
  This allows Spring to scan and execute scheduled methods automatically.
    @EnableScheduling
    @SpringBootApplication
    public class Application {
    }
2. Basic @Scheduled Job
  We use @Scheduled on a method to make it run automatically.
  Method should be void and typically contains background logic.
    @Component
    public class MyJob {
        @Scheduled(fixedRate = 5000)
        public void execute() {
            System.out.println("Job executed");
        }
    }
3. Fixed Rate Scheduling
  Executes at a fixed interval based on start time, even if previous execution is still running.
  Useful for polling or monitoring systems.
    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 5000)
    public void pollService() {
        System.out.println("Polling external service every 5 seconds");
    }
4. Fixed Delay Scheduling
  Executes after the previous execution is completed + delay time.
  Prevents overlapping execution.
    @Scheduled(fixedDelay = 5000)
    public void processData() throws InterruptedException {
        Thread.sleep(3000); // simulate long task
        System.out.println("Processed after delay");
    }
5. Cron-Based Scheduling
  Used for time-based jobs like daily or weekly tasks.
  Most common in production systems.
    @Scheduled(cron = "0 0 2 * * ?")
    public void dailyJob() {
        System.out.println("Runs every day at 2 AM");
    }
6. Default Single Thread Behavior
  By default, Spring runs all scheduled jobs in a single thread.
  If one job is slow, others will be delayed.
    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 5000)
    public void slowJob() throws InterruptedException {
        Thread.sleep(10000); // blocks scheduler
        System.out.println("Slow job finished");
    }
7. Configure Thread Pool (Parallel Execution)
  To avoid blocking, we configure a thread pool scheduler.
  Allows multiple jobs to run concurrently.
    @Configuration
    @EnableScheduling
    public class SchedulerConfig {
    
        @Bean
        public TaskScheduler taskScheduler() {
            ThreadPoolTaskScheduler scheduler = new ThreadPoolTaskScheduler();
            scheduler.setPoolSize(5);
            scheduler.setThreadNamePrefix("Scheduler-");
            return scheduler;
        }
    }
8. Handling Multiple Instances (Distributed Systems)
  In microservices, all instances will run the same job → duplicate execution issue.
  We use locking to ensure only one instance executes.
  To handle this, we implement mechanisms like:
        Database locking (ensuring only one instance runs the job)
        Distributed locks (Redis/Zookeeper)
        Using Quartz in cluster mode

    Example (DB Lock Concept)
    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 10000)
    public void job() {
        if (lockService.acquireLock("JOB_LOCK")) {
            try {
                System.out.println("Executing job safely");
            } finally {
                lockService.releaseLock("JOB_LOCK");
            }
        }
    }
9. Error Handling
  Always wrap logic in try-catch to handle failures gracefully.
  Helps in logging and monitoring.
    @Scheduled(fixedRate = 5000)
    public void safeJob() {
        try {
            int result = 10 / 0; // error
        } catch (Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Error occurred: " + e.getMessage());
        }
    }
10. Long-Running Jobs (Async Handling)
  Long-running tasks should not block scheduler threads.
  We can offload heavy processing using:
      @Async for parallel execution
      Messaging systems like Kafka or RabbitMQ
  This ensures scheduler remains responsive.

      Use @Async for parallel execution.
          @Async
          @Scheduled(fixedRate = 5000)
          public void asyncJob() throws InterruptedException {
              Thread.sleep(8000);
              System.out.println("Async job running");
          }

   Also enable async:@EnableAsync
11. Dynamic Scheduling (Config-Based)
    Cron expression can be externalized to config.
    Allows runtime changes without redeployment.
        @Scheduled(cron = "${job.cron}")
        public void dynamicJob() {
            System.out.println("Dynamic schedule job");
        }
        job.cron=0 0/1 * * * ?
12. Quartz Scheduler (Advanced)
  Used for enterprise-grade scheduling with persistence and clustering.
  For enterprise use cases, @Scheduled is sometimes not enough.
  Quartz is preferred when we need:
        Job persistence (store job state in DB)
        Retry and failure handling
        Clustering (only one instance executes job)
        Complex workflows and dependencies
  Example Job
      public class QuartzJob implements Job {
          public void execute(JobExecutionContext context) {
              System.out.println("Quartz job executed");
          }
      }
  Trigger Configuration
        @Bean
        public JobDetail jobDetail() {
            return JobBuilder.newJob(QuartzJob.class)
                    .withIdentity("job1")
                    .storeDurably()
                    .build();
        }

