Scaling Options
Spring Batch offers four main ways to scale when a single-threaded job is too slow:
Multi-threaded Step — each chunk runs on a separate thread using a TaskExecutor. 
                    Simple to configure but the ItemReader must be thread-safe.
Parallel Steps — independent Steps run simultaneously using a Flow with a SplitState. 
                Good when your job has unrelated phases.
Partitioning — a manager Step splits the data into partitions (e.g. by ID range or file), and worker Steps process each partition in parallel
                  — locally via threads or remotely via messaging.
Remote Chunking — the manager reads items and sends them over a message queue (RabbitMQ, Kafka); remote workers do the processing and writing.
                  Best for CPU-heavy processing tasks.

Minimal Spring Boot Setup:
@Configuration
@EnableBatchProcessing
public class BatchConfig {
    @Bean
    public Job importJob(JobRepository repo, Step step1) {
        return new JobBuilder("importJob", repo)
                .start(step1)
                .build();
    }
    @Bean
    public Step step1(JobRepository repo,
                      PlatformTransactionManager txm,
                      ItemReader<User> reader,
                      ItemProcessor<User, UserDto> processor,
                      ItemWriter<UserDto> writer) {
        return new StepBuilder("step1", repo)
                .<User, UserDto>chunk(100, txm)  // chunk size = 100
                .reader(reader)
                .processor(processor)
                .writer(writer)
                .faultTolerant()
                .skip(FlatFileParseException.class)
                .skipLimit(10)
                .build();
    }
}
The chunk(100, txm) call means: read and process 100 items, then write all 100 in one transaction. 
If that transaction fails, only those 100 items are rolled back — not the entire job.

Cron Job Integration with Spring Batch
Spring Batch does not schedule itself. You need a trigger. The three common approaches:
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  HOW JOBS GET TRIGGERED                         │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  OPTION 1: Spring @Scheduled (built-in, simple)
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────
  @Scheduled(cron = "0 0 2 * * *")   ← runs every day at 2:00 AM
  public void runJob() {
      JobParameters params = new JobParametersBuilder()
          .addLong("run.id", System.currentTimeMillis())
          .toJobParameters();
      jobLauncher.run(importJob, params);
  }

  OPTION 2: Quartz Scheduler (distributed, clustered)
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  QuartzJobBean → triggers JobLauncher → runs Spring Batch Job
  Quartz stores trigger state in DB → safe for clustered environments

  OPTION 3: External Trigger (CI/CD, Kubernetes CronJob, etc.)
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  kubectl CronJob → HTTP POST /api/jobs/trigger
                 → REST Controller → JobLauncher.run()


