  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
       │
       ▼
  TARGET DB (new schema / different DB vendor)


┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│              PAGING vs CURSOR — CHOOSING THE RIGHT READER               │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  JdbcCursorItemReader
  ────────────────────
  Opens ONE DB connection → streams rows via cursor
  Fast, but holds connection for entire step duration
  Risk: connection timeout on very long jobs
  Best for: moderate data, fast network, same DB server

  JdbcPagingItemReader
  ────────────────────
  Issues a new SQL query per page → releases connection after each page
  Slower but safe for hours-long jobs
  Needs a sort key (e.g. ORDER BY id) for stable pagination
  Best for: huge datasets, cross-network DB calls, cloud DBs

  SELECT * FROM orders
  WHERE id > :lastId        ← offset-free pagination (faster)
  ORDER BY id
  LIMIT 1000

ExecutorService + TaskExecutor in Spring Batch
This is how you go from single-threaded (slow) to parallel (fast) processing.
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│               THREADING MODEL — FROM SLOW TO FAST                       │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  DEFAULT (single-threaded) — processes one chunk at a time
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Main Thread:
  [Read 1000]──►[Process]──►[Write]──►[Read 1000]──►[Process]──►[Write]
  Time: T1────────────────────────────────────────────────────────► slow


  MULTI-THREADED STEP — each chunk on its own thread
  ────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Thread-1: [Read chunk-1]──►[Process]──►[Write]
  Thread-2: [Read chunk-2]──►[Process]──►[Write]
  Thread-3: [Read chunk-3]──►[Process]──►[Write]
  Thread-4: [Read chunk-4]──►[Process]──►[Write]
  Time: T1──────────────────────────────────────► much faster

  ⚠ WARNING: ItemReader MUST be thread-safe
             Use SynchronizedItemStreamReader wrapper


┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│               TASKEXECUTOR CONFIGURATION                                │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  @Bean
  public TaskExecutor taskExecutor() {
      ThreadPoolTaskExecutor executor = new ThreadPoolTaskExecutor();
      executor.setCorePoolSize(5);       // always-alive threads
      executor.setMaxPoolSize(10);       // burst capacity
      executor.setQueueCapacity(25);     // pending chunk queue
      executor.setThreadNamePrefix("batch-thread-");
      executor.initialize();
      return executor;
  }

  @Bean
  public Step multiThreadedStep(...) {
      return new StepBuilder("step", repo)
              .<Source, Target>chunk(1000, txm)
              .reader(reader)
              .processor(processor)
              .writer(writer)
              .taskExecutor(taskExecutor())   // ← plug it in here
              .throttleLimit(10)              // max concurrent chunks
              .build();
  }


┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│               THREAD POOL SIZING GUIDE                                  │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  CPU-bound processing (heavy computation):
      corePoolSize = number of CPU cores (e.g. 8)

  I/O-bound processing (DB reads/writes, network calls):
      corePoolSize = 2× to 4× CPU cores (e.g. 16–32)
      because threads spend most time waiting on I/O

  DB connection pool must be >= maxPoolSize
  otherwise threads will block waiting for a connection
  HikariCP maxPoolSize >= batch ThreadPool maxPoolSize

Partitioning — The Right Way to Scale DB Migration
Multi-threaded step shares one reader. Partitioning gives each thread its own reader, its own data slice, its own transaction. Much safer and more scalable.
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    PARTITIONING ARCHITECTURE                            │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  Total rows in source DB: 10,000,000

  ┌──────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │           MANAGER STEP (single thread)           │
  │                                                  │
  │  Partitioner splits data into ranges:            │
  │  Partition-1 → id: 1        to  1,000,000        │
  │  Partition-2 → id: 1,000,001 to 2,000,000        │
  │  Partition-3 → id: 2,000,001 to 3,000,000        │
  │  ...                                             │
  │  Partition-10→ id: 9,000,001 to 10,000,000       │
  └──────────────────────┬───────────────────────────┘
                         │ delegates to
          ┌──────────────┼──────────────┐
          ▼              ▼              ▼
   ┌─────────────┐ ┌─────────────┐ ┌─────────────┐
   │  Worker-1   │ │  Worker-2   │ │  Worker-3   │ ... 10 workers
   │  ids 1-1M   │ │  ids 1M-2M  │ │  ids 2M-3M  │
   │  Reader     │ │  Reader     │ │  Reader     │
   │  Processor  │ │  Processor  │ │  Processor  │
   │  Writer     │ │  Writer     │ │  Writer     │
   └─────────────┘ └─────────────┘ └─────────────┘
          │              │              │
          └──────────────┼──────────────┘
                         ▼
                   TARGET DATABASE
                   (all 10M rows written)


