  │   - map old schema columns to new schema                        │
  │   - normalize dates, enums, nulls                               │
  │   - enrich with lookup data (cached in memory)                  │
  │       │                                                         │
  │       ▼                                                         │
  │  JdbcBatchItemWriter (target DB, batch INSERT 1000 rows)        │
  │                                                                 │
  │  ThreadPool: 10 threads, HikariCP: 20 connections               │
  │  Duration: minutes to hours depending on data volume            │
  └────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
                               │ COMPLETED
                               ▼
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  Step 3 — VALIDATION (Tasklet)                                  │
  │  SELECT COUNT(*) FROM source  vs  SELECT COUNT(*) FROM target   │
  │  If mismatch → throw exception → Step fails → alerts fire       │
  └────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
                               │ COMPLETED
                               ▼
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  Step 4 — INDEX REBUILD (Tasklet)                               │
  │  Re-enable indexes on target DB that were disabled for bulk load │
  └────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
                               │ COMPLETED
                               ▼
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  Step 5 — NOTIFY (Tasklet)                                      │
  │  Send success email / Slack alert with row counts & duration    │
  └────────────────────────────┬────────────────────────────────────┘
                               │
                               ▼
                       JOB COMPLETED ✓
                  All metadata saved in JobRepository
                  Re-run same date params → SKIPPED (already complete)


  ON ANY STEP FAILURE:
  ─────────────────────
  JobRepository records FAILED status + step name + exception
  Re-trigger job with same date params
  Spring Batch skips already-COMPLETED steps
  Resumes from the FAILED step automatically

Fault Tolerance — Skip, Retry, Restart
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                     FAULT TOLERANCE STRATEGIES                          │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  SKIP — tolerate bad records without stopping the job
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  .faultTolerant()
  .skip(FlatFileParseException.class)   ← skip unparseable rows
  .skip(ConstraintViolationException.class) ← skip duplicate keys
  .skipLimit(500)                        ← but fail if >500 skipped

  What happens to skipped items?
  → Logged by ItemSkipListener
  → Written to a separate error table or dead-letter file
  → Job continues with remaining records


  RETRY — handle transient failures automatically
  ─────────────────────────────────────────────────
  .faultTolerant()
  .retry(DeadlockLoserDataAccessException.class)
  .retry(TransientDataAccessException.class)
  .retryLimit(3)     ← try up to 3 times before skipping/failing

  Retry sequence for one item:
  Attempt 1 → fails (deadlock)
  Wait (back-off policy)
  Attempt 2 → fails (deadlock)
  Wait
  Attempt 3 → success ✓  (or → skip if still failing)


  RESTART — resume from exact failure point
  ───────────────────────────────────────────
  Job fails at Step 2, chunk 450 (after 449,000 rows written)
       │
       ▼
  JobRepository stores: Step2.writeCount=449000
                        Step2.status=FAILED
                        ExecutionContext={lastProcessedId=449000}
       │
  Re-trigger same job + same JobParameters
       │
       ▼
  Step 1 → SKIPPED (already COMPLETED)
  Step 2 → RESUMED from id=449001 onward
  No duplicate writes, no data loss


┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                  SKIP vs RETRY vs RESTART — WHEN TO USE                 │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  SKIP   → bad data (corrupt records, constraint violations)
           you accept losing those rows, log them separately

  RETRY  → transient infrastructure issues (deadlocks, timeouts)
           the error is temporary, same data will succeed next attempt

  RESTART→ job-level failure (OOM, DB down, server crash)
           infrastructure recovered, resume job from failure point

Monitoring and Observability
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    WHAT SPRING BATCH TRACKS                             │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  BATCH_JOB_INSTANCE       → job name + parameters (unique run identity)
  BATCH_JOB_EXECUTION      → start time, end time, status, exit message
  BATCH_JOB_EXEC_PARAMS    → parameters stored per execution
  BATCH_STEP_EXECUTION     → per-step: readCount, writeCount, skipCount,
